# PulseBoard Channel Plugin — Implementation Plan

## Context

This plan adds a new fictional **PulseBoard** channel plugin to OpenClaw. PulseBoard is an imaginary real-time bulletin board messaging platform where users post messages to named **boards** (group channels, identified as `#board-name`) and can also send **direct messages** between usernames. The plugin must:

- Support both `direct` and `group` chat types
- Enforce a 4000-character text chunk limit
- Follow the exact same bundled extension structure as existing channel plugins (Nostr is the primary template; IRC is referenced for group-chat patterns)
- Live entirely in `extensions/pulseboard/` — **no existing files modified**

---

## File Tree to Create

```
extensions/pulseboard/
├── openclaw.plugin.json        # Manifest (id + channels)
├── package.json                # @openclaw/pulseboard + openclaw.channel block
├── index.ts                    # defineChannelPluginEntry entry point
├── api.ts                      # Public export barrel
├── runtime-api.ts              # Private runtime barrel (SDK re-exports)
├── setup-entry.ts              # defineSetupPluginEntry (setup-only entry)
└── src/
    ├── channel.ts              # Main ChannelPlugin via createChatChannelPlugin()
    ├── config-schema.ts        # Zod schema for channels.pulseboard.*
    ├── types.ts                # Config types + account resolution helpers
    ├── runtime.ts              # createPluginRuntimeStore
    ├── setup-surface.ts        # ChannelSetupAdapter + ChannelSetupWizard
    ├── send.ts                 # sendPulseBoardMessage() stub helper
    └── channel.test.ts         # Unit tests
```

---

## Naming Invariants

From `src/plugins/bundled-plugin-naming.test.ts`:

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Directory name | `pulseboard` |
| `openclaw.plugin.json` → `id` | `pulseboard` |
| `package.json` → `name` | `@openclaw/pulseboard` |
| `package.json` → `openclaw.channel.id` | `pulseboard` |
| `openclaw.install.npmSpec` (if present) | must equal `@openclaw/pulseboard` |

This plugin is fictional and not published to npm, so `openclaw.install` is omitted entirely.

